{
  "texts": [
    "More precisely, what is the algorithmic level and what is the computational level of ethical problems posed by normative theory (NT)?",
    "First, we note that normative ethics blurs the line between Marr's first two levels.",
    "In particular, its prescriptive component is intimately linked with its action-guidance, i.e., by answering what is good (e.g., adherence to moral duties), it tells you how to do good (e.g., only perform actions that adhere to moral duties).",
    "14 In turn, this opens up a range of possible interpretations, and we will address three:",
    "(1) NT as algorithmic-level solution to generalized morality In the most general sense, if the computational-level problem is phrased as \"do what is moral\", we might interpret an NT as an algorithmic-level solution to the computational problem \"how to be moral in general\"."
  ]
}